    <node id="1. Healthier model for education: The speakers discuss two approaches from certain states in the United States and Hong Kong. In some states in the US, they produce a state textbook which can be a strong model if there is independence and no strong political influence. On the other hand, Hong Kong, a high-performing jurisdiction, is trying to move away from the textbook model and de-emphasize textbooks, focusing more on other resources.&#10;2. Importance of resources supporting assessment objectives: Gareth Pierce emphasizes the need for resources that support assessment objectives focused on analysis and evaluation, as they have shifted towards these skills in many subjects. He raises questions about whether some content should be available during assessments and encourages debate with the qualifications regulator on this matter.&#10;&#10;In summary, providing a healthier model for education in the future could involve moving away from a strong reliance on textbooks, ensuring independence in state models, or de-emphasizing textbooks altogether. Additionally, it is important to develop resources that support assessment objectives focusing on analysis and evaluation to cater to the shifts in learning goals in various subjects." />
    <node id="—then that provides an opportunity for, I would suggest, a much healthier model in the future. There are various ways of doing that. In the United States, for example, there are some states within the United States that produce a state textbook. Now, that can have issues, particularly if it's politically orientated—so, if politicians are seen to have a strong influence in the content that's taught. But if there is independence in that state model, then I think that can be quite strong model. Equally, if you look at somewhere like Hong Kong, they've actually tried to de-emphasise textbooks. So, Hong Kong, which is a very high-performing jurisdiction, is trying to move away from that model in the future.&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: Could I just add very, very briefly—&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Very briefly, because I want to bring Hefin in.&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: I know that, in our letter to you, we emphasised that this is not just to do with the body of knowledge. The assessment objectives have shifted in many subjects towards analysis and evaluation. So, therefore, we really do need resources that support" />
    <node id=" who should be responsible for developing these curriculum resources?&#10;Speaker: Philip Blaker&#10;Content: I think, for a new model, that needs to be determined. Welsh Government has a role in curriculum at the moment. They have responsibility for curriclum and they've already started work with the seminar last year, and then drawing people together now to look at a new model for the future. I think we need to evolve that approach, and I think Welsh Government taking a lead on some of this thinking about how things might be prepared for the future is probably a good position to be in at the moment.&#10;Speaker: Darren Millar AM&#10;Content: Are there any other models that you can point us to in terms of how these things are done elsewhere?&#10;Speaker: Philip Blaker&#10;Content: Yes, there are models where you can have—. For example, in Northern Ireland, you have the regulator, the awarding body and the curriculum body all under one roof. So, you can have a position where everything is tied together as it is in Northern Ireland with the Council for the Curriculum, Examinations and Assessment. Equally, if you look at somewhere like Hong Kong, you have very distinct bodies that are looking after each" />
    <node id=" and I think that that's a very positive thing. But, how do you differentiate between the different learning styles of individual students who are in that cohort to ensure that the disadvantage that one faces because they're somebody who relies particularly heavily on textbook-type learning, traditional sort of swotting up for examinations, versus someone who is much more digitally aware and able to use digital resources—? How do you make sure that it's fair to the cohort as a whole, while still enabling some of these individuals for whom textbooks are important not to face disadvantage within that cohort?&#10;Speaker: Philip Blaker&#10;Content: The systems that are in place are very much around making sure that awarding is fair across the whole cohort. It's very difficult—in fact, it would be impossible—to unpick all of the different factors that might affect performance, because you could well have a textbook that's been available for some time, it may be somebody's preferred leaning style to use a textbook, but did they use that textbook effectively? You know, did they open it in revision or did they not open it in revision? So, there are so many different factors that can affect individual performance. I think it's impossible to unpick" />
    <node id="1. For new textbooks being developed, the Welsh-medium version will be completed and published simultaneously with the English version. The Welsh version will be translated from the English original, with editing and translation happening concurrently as the textbook is written. An eight-week period has been agreed upon for this process, to ensure that both versions are available at the same time. Draft versions of the English textbook may be made available earlier, but final publication will be held until the Welsh version is complete.&#10;2. However, if an English version of a textbook is already late in development, the agreed-upon eight-week period for translation and editing may not apply. This is because the focus is on ensuring equity in the release of new textbooks moving forward, rather than delaying texts that have already been delayed.&#10;3. It's important to note that producing Welsh-medium textbooks first and then translating them into English is an approach that publishers like Hodder and Illuminate are open to, but it has not been the standard practice in the past. This new approach is being implemented as an experiment at the request of the Welsh Government." />
    <node id="1. Teaching to the test: Creating more sample assessments may lead to a higher risk of &quot;teaching to the test,&quot; which refers to tailoring classroom instruction and activities to specifically align with the content and format of standardized assessments. This can result in a narrowed curriculum focus, limiting opportunities for students to develop a broader range of skills and knowledge.&#10;2. Mitigating issues through future reforms: One way to mitigate these potential risks is by adjusting the timeline for producing resources like textbooks and other curriculum materials that support assessment objectives focusing on analysis and evaluation. By shifting the emphasis from textbooks as the primary resource towards a variety of resources, educators can create more diverse learning experiences that do not solely focus on test-taking strategies or content.&#10;&#10;In summary, while creating more sample assessments can provide valuable practice materials for students, it also poses risks related to teaching to the test and may inadvertently narrow the curriculum's scope. By carefully considering the production timeline of curriculum resources like textbooks and diversifying available learning materials, future reforms can help mitigate these issues and promote a more balanced approach to education." />
