    <node id="&#10;Content: Our view in the WJEC is that subsidy will be necessary. But we could rethink the model for the subsidy, perhaps. At the moment, the subsidy is described as a subsidy for the Welsh-medium version. Why not rethink that and think of a subsidy for producing resources in two languages for the Welsh curriculum? And perhaps we would need a little more funding for that. But there will be organisations such as the WJEC who will still be interested in contributing, because we are a charity, and within our mission is investment in various things that supports education in Wales.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffydd AM&#10;Content: But in terms of where we are now, resources have to be translated. I struggle at times to understand why it takes so much time to translate a resource. I would like to know better, perhaps, what the main barriers are in that sense. But also, how long is acceptable to wait for a translation, in your view?&#10;Speaker: Mike Ebbsworth&#10;Content: We've done a great deal of work recently, over recent years, to ensure that that delay between having an English version and a Welsh version is reduced. We are highly aware of the fact that the best" />
    <node id=" England preclude examination bodies from having commercial links with providers of textbooks, but that is something that emerges from the three-nation regime that existed in terms of qualifications. So, that is one point that we noted as something that needs to be considered for Wales as we move forward, whether it would be possible—. As we are not talking about examination boards competing with each other in Wales for GCSE and A-levels, in passing, that is something that I would want to suggest may deserve review. We encourage publishers to take an interest. At the moment, these tend to be England-based—Hodder Education and Illuminate Education, for example—and then the Welsh Government does provide funding to the WJEC to support the process of providing Welsh-language versions for those textbooks. So, we use that funding to provide editorial support to the process, and also to pay for translation costs, and we give significant guidance in terms of terminology. We have a language services team including excellent editors and translators within the WJEC, and we work closely with external translators too, and we use translation technology increasingly, which facilitates a great many things. Beyond that, I think the WJEC does see the need for flexibility, particularly when difficulties arise, and you" />
    <node id="1. Yes, a textbook is considered a fundamental resource for learners and teachers, particularly during exam periods when students need to &quot;swot up&quot; on information. This sentiment is expressed by Darren Millar AM in the transcript.&#10;2. The Welsh Government, WJEC, and publishers are currently implementing an experiment to ensure equity in the release of new textbooks in both Welsh and English languages. This decision aims to address concerns about different timetables for the availability of learning materials in different languages.&#10;3. The agreement between the involved parties is not a mandate but rather a collaboration to create a national approach for resource creation, as mentioned by Gareth Pierce. The focus is on creating a common core of resources available for learners and teachers, with new textbooks being produced simultaneously in both languages when possible.&#10;4. The challenge lies in the fact that most publishers and authors work through the medium of English, causing delays in the production of Welsh-medium materials. The experiment aims to change this practice by prioritizing Welsh versions first, then translating them into English. This approach is being applied only to textbooks currently in development, as stated by Mike Ebbsworth.&#10;5. Both Darren Millar AM and Mike Ebbsworth acknowledge the need for improving the availability of both Welsh-medium and English language resources, with Millar sharing personal experiences related to his daughter's exam preparations. They agree on the importance of textbooks as fundamental learning resources, especially during exam periods." />
    <node id=" you. Darren Millar.&#10;Speaker: Darren Millar AM&#10;Content: This is a huge mess, isn't it? It's a huge mess, which is causing lots of pressure and extra work for teachers, lots of pressure and extra work for learners, and is affecting the well-being of students, at a time when they need to be mentally fit, in order to go through the general stress that learners face when they have exams coming up. We know that the problems are not confined to Welsh-medium resources; they're also being experienced in English language resources as well, particularly in terms of the availability of textbooks. You've both mentioned—both of your organisations have mentioned that there needs to be some sort of common core of resources available for learners and teachers, and I would agree with you on that front. But isn't a textbook a pretty basic element of anybody's toolkit for supporting a child getting through the information that they need to learn, and swot up on, in advance of exams?&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: I think that the evidence is that different learners see their requirements differently. And I agree that a textbook is part of the picture that should be available. But I think the evidence also shows that not every young" />
    <node id=" often in English medium, but we know about that gap in time in the Welsh provision.&#10;Speaker: Darren Millar AM&#10;Content: Well, it's happened fairly regularly in the English-medium textbook world, hasn't it? My daughter—she featured in that video—has got her RS qualifications coming up, and she only had a textbook over the Easter period. I mean, it's completely unacceptable. And many others in that video are also being affected. You mentioned digital resources; not everybody's got access to digital resources in their own homes, even, in Wales. So, aren't we giving a significant disadvantage to those learners who might need the traditional 'swotting up from a textbook' method of revision and benefit from that?&#10;Speaker: Mike Ebbsworth&#10;Content: We do ensure that those digital resources include things that the teachers can also print. Most of these are resources for teachers so that the teachers can adapt them for their own use, to suit the learners who are in front of them at any given time. But certainly there are materials there. If there are activities, then those activities can be printed off and handed to pupils so that they can take them home. So, I would" />
    <node id="1. Collaboration and Identification of High-Quality Resources: To utilize both English and Welsh resources effectively in Welsh-medium schools, there should be collaboration between schools and stakeholders to identify high-quality resources worth translating. This can help prevent duplication of efforts and optimize teachers' time.&#10;&#10;2. National Approach for Resource Creation: The Welsh Government, WJEC, and publishers are working together to create a national approach for resource creation, focusing on developing a common core of resources available for learners and teachers in both languages. This includes an experiment to ensure equity in the release of new textbooks in both Welsh and English.&#10;&#10;3. Awareness of Digitally Available Resources: Gareth Pierce mentioned that there are many resources available digitally in both languages at the same time. Teachers should be made aware of these resources to reduce the need for independent translations and duplication of efforts.&#10;&#10;4. Balancing Act between Languages: The vision for teaching in Welsh-medium classes should aim to enrich the learning experience by taking advantage of both the Welsh language and English resources. This can help create a more comprehensive and balanced educational environment.&#10;&#10;5. Addressing the Root Cause of Translation Needs: It is essential to understand what causes the need for translations in order to address the issue effectively. By identifying the source of the problem, stakeholders can work together to find solutions that benefit both learners and teachers." />
    <node id="1. Teaching to the test: Creating more sample assessments can increase the risk of &quot;teaching to the test,&quot; where classroom instruction is tailored to specifically align with the content and format of standardized assessments. This narrows the curriculum's scope, limiting opportunities for students to develop a broader range of skills and knowledge.&#10;2. Weakening real assessments: By providing too many sample assessment materials containing examiners' ideas, there is a risk of weakening the value and validity of actual assessments, as teachers may rely on these samples instead of developing their own robust assessment methods.&#10;3. Reduced focus on deeper learning: An overemphasis on sample assessments could shift attention away from deeper learning objectives like analysis and evaluation towards test-taking strategies or content mastery. This may not adequately prepare students for the demands of real-world situations or higher education.&#10;4. Lower reliability of teacher predictions: Historically, there has been a low correlation between predicted and achieved grades, suggesting that comparing teacher assessments to actual grade outcomes on a sample basis might not provide highly reliable evidence. Therefore, creating more sample assessments may not significantly improve the accuracy of teacher predictions or reduce the risk of teaching to the test." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh government has allocated a £500,000 grant to support the creation and translation of educational resources, primarily focusing on editorial and translation costs. Some flexibility in the allocation of this fund may be possible, as mentioned during discussions between Mike Ebbsworth, Lynne Neagle AM, and Darren Millar AM.&#10;2. The grant will help ensure that ongoing publications are available in both Welsh and English mediums, with a percentage of the funding supporting Welsh-medium resources. This allocation is not a mandate but rather a collaboration between the WJEC, publishers, and the Welsh government to create a national approach for resource creation.&#10;3. The agreement aims to reduce delays in releasing Welsh-medium materials compared to their English counterparts. A new approach involves prioritizing Welsh versions first, then translating them into English when possible, starting with textbooks currently in development.&#10;4. Both Darren Millar AM and Mike Ebbsworth recognize the need for improving the availability of both Welsh-medium and English language resources, emphasizing textbooks as fundamental learning resources, especially during exam periods.&#10;5. WJEC has proposed rethinking the subsidy model to support producing resources in two languages for the Welsh curriculum instead of just providing a subsidy for Welsh-medium versions. They are open to contributing more funding to this new approach.&#10;6. There is an ongoing discussion about the length of time it takes to translate resources and what an acceptable waiting period would be. The goal is to reduce delays, with WJEC succeeding in agreeing on an eight-week turnaround for translating Welsh versions of textbooks in development." />
    <node id=" working on along with publishers, and where we would like to make a claim against that grant to pay for the editorial and translation costs that we will have incurred. Now, there have been conversations recently about possible support from that grant for some research work into the use of various materials and resources, and also, although this would be a very small part, a contribution towards seminars for publishers. But that isn't a full picture of the £500,000; I think you would have to ask the Welsh Government about the exact allocation of that total fund. But there may be some flexibility. We've just started this financial year; I'm sure there is some flexibility in their thinking in terms of the use of some of this resource. Do you want to add anything, Mike?&#10;Speaker: Mike Ebbsworth&#10;Content: Certainly. We have contributed a list of publications, for example, that are ongoing, and they're aware of that, and a percentage of that funding then will go towards ensuring that those are there through the medium of Welsh.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Darren Millar.&#10;Speaker: Darren Millar AM&#10;Content: This is a huge mess, isn't it? It's a huge mess" />
    <node id="1. Teacher autonomy is important in interpreting and providing the curriculum because it enables teachers to adapt the curriculum to their students' needs, contexts, and interests. This can lead to more engaged learners and more effective teaching. The consortia emphasize this autonomy, suggesting that there might be less need for national resources or that such resources should support teachers' autonomy.&#10;2. Changes in regulations could encourage Welsh providers like the WJEC to take on a larger role in addressing the shortage of providers in Wales by creating an enabling environment for them to participate in the market. For instance, if regulations are revised to allow the WJEC to engage more actively in producing and publishing resources, it might be more inclined to fill gaps in the market and contribute to a more diverse range of offerings for Welsh schools.&#10;&#10;In summary, teacher autonomy is important for tailoring curriculum delivery to students' needs, while adjustments to regulations could incentivize Welsh providers like the WJEC to play a larger role in addressing the shortage of resource providers in Wales." />
    <node id=" Pierce&#10;Content: Just one very brief comment in that context: I think that the comment of the consortia jointly is important there. They emphasise, in the context of the curriculum, the importance of the autonomy of teachers in interpreting and providing, therefore I think we truly need to discuss that. Does that suggest that there won't be so much need for national resources, or are those resources required to support that autonomy in any case? We need to discuss that at an early stage and in detail, I think.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffydd AM&#10;Content: Yes, certainly, and one is concerned that that conversation isn't already happening, but, yes, okay, you've made that point clearly. If I could return, therefore, to the commercial issue—clearly, there is a shortage of providers in Wales, and we are reliant on others. You suggested that the WJEC may be interested in stepping up and taking some sort of role if regulations were changed. I assume that that would be something that you would be eager to see happening in terms of the change to regulation in that context.&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: Yes, and we've been part of starting that discussion amongst publishers in Wales. Certainly" />
    <node id=" those qualifications are delivered securely and fairly. I would say a strength of the Welsh model is that there is an independent regulator and a single awarding body largely, because much of the work that Ofqual would need to do in terms of its maintenance of standards is about ensuring that the competition between awarding bodies doesn't lead to what's been termed in the past as a race to the bottom in terms of standards. Now, the opportunity that we have in Wales is, where we have a single awarding body, we can have a close and good working relationship with WJEC, but guarding very strongly to make sure that we keep that regulatory distance to make sure that we preserve our role as the regulator and look at WJEC as one of our regulated bodies.&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: Can I make a general point? Perhaps the important opportunity in Wales is to look anew at how national and regional organisations, such as the consortia, can collaborate to make a success of the broad range of resources and CPD that will be required to support the new curriculum, and also the next set of qualifications that will be reformed. We've referred to many organisations today, but there are others. The Welsh Books Council, for example, is part of" />
    <node id="1. The £500,000 funding for Welsh-medium educational resources in the 2018-19 budget will be used to support the creation and translation of a range of educational materials into Welsh. This budget is allocated by the Welsh Government and managed by organizations like WJEC (Welsh Joint Education Committee).&#10;2. The funding will cover editorial and translation costs incurred while working with publishers on various resources for Welsh-medium education. These resources may include textbooks, multimedia materials, assessment tools, and other educational aids.&#10;3. By having this budget dedicated to Welsh-medium educational resources, the Welsh Government aims to ensure that teachers and students have access to high-quality learning materials in their native language, reducing barriers to learning and promoting bilingual education.&#10;4. The allocation of funds will likely be determined through discussions between the Welsh Government, WJEC, and publishers, ensuring that resources are developed according to the needs of Welsh-medium schools and teachers. This process helps prioritize investments in areas where they are most needed and can have the greatest impact on teaching and learning.&#10;5. It is important to note that the funds specifically target the development of a core, common body of knowledge bilingually, allowing teachers to access essential educational resources in both Welsh and English without having to spend time translating these materials themselves. This approach enables educators to focus more on teaching and lesson planning rather than translation tasks." />
    <node id=". And what I wouldn't want to see is a default position where all materials were bilingual—a wide range of resources that might be created from all sorts of diverse, different channels—because that may inhibit the creation of some of those materials that may be more creative, which could then be used by teachers as they see appropriate. But I think it is reasonable to expect for that core, common body of knowledge to be available bilingually by default, and for teachers not to have to spend time translating that.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you. A final question from me, then. The £500,000 funding for Welsh-medium educational resource that's in the budget for 2018-19—are you able to share any information with the committee as to how that's going to be spent?&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: Tthe WJEC has some information in terms of that budget. It is a Welsh Government budget, and they have annual discussions with us as to what resources we are likely to be working on along with publishers, and where we would like to make a claim against that grant to pay for the editorial and translation costs that we will have incurred." />
    <node id="Yes, it is accepted that some students have been negatively affected by the lack of suitable support materials for general qualifications. There is evidence of their concern, even though it may be challenging to establish a direct cause-and-effect relationship between anxiety from resource limitations and lower attainment due to the presence of multiple factors and resources that could impact student performance." />
    <node id=" of the lack of resources, we heard on the video, as you've just mentioned, Gareth, that pupils were experiencing a lot of stress and anxiety, and it affected their well-being in terms of their perception that they might be disadvantaged by the lack of resources, as we discussed. We know exam time is very, very stressful—I'm sure all of us would agree with that—in general, without any additional problems or perceptions of problems. So, with that sort of background, would you accept then that some students have been negatively affected by the lack of suitable support materials for general qualifications? I know we've discussed this in terms of it being difficult, perhaps, to show cause and effect, but I think most people watching that video would clearly come to the view that some students have been negatively impacted. Would you accept that?&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: I'd have to agree. There is evidence of their concern, isn't there? But as Philip said, what we don't have is evidence that that anxiety then has an impact on their attainment, because there are so many factors, there are so many different kinds of resources that they've referred to—even those who want to see textbooks, they're also talking about so many other materials" />
    <node id="Yes, there is a fundamental unfairness in the current education system when some students do not have access to supportive materials based on their specific subjects or languages of study. This disparity can lead to unequal opportunities for learning and academic success.&#10;&#10;Improving digital accessibility and literacy can help address this issue by providing more equitable access to various resources, regardless of a student's subject or language. Digital materials can be easily updated, shared, and distributed, which makes it possible to create and disseminate resources in multiple languages and cater to different subjects more efficiently. Additionally, digital learning environments support diverse learning styles, allowing students to engage with content through multimedia formats that suit their individual needs.&#10;&#10;However, while digital resources can help bridge gaps in access to supportive materials, they also pose risks related to teaching to the test and narrowing the curriculum's scope. Careful consideration should be given to the production timeline of curriculum resources like textbooks and diversifying available learning materials to promote a more balanced approach to education.&#10;&#10;In summary, addressing the fundamental unfairness in the current education system requires improving digital accessibility and literacy, as well as carefully considering the design and distribution of supportive materials to ensure equal opportunities for all students, regardless of their subject or language of study." />
    <node id=", there are so many different kinds of resources that they've referred to—even those who want to see textbooks, they're also talking about so many other materials that are available to them. Of course, it's also clear that they are conscientious young people who have worked hard, so you have a picture there of young people who are concerned, yes, and as you've said, examinations are a stressful time in general, but they are also young people who are doing their level best, and usually do get the results that they have worked for. That's the evidence that we have: the results tend to be achieved.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: Okay. Coming back again to matters that we've already discussed, but just to put to you in a fairly focused way, would you accept that it isn't fair that some pupils are not having the support material that others are having, depending on whether their particular subject is involved and the language that they're studying through? Would you accept that that is a basic unfairness in the system as it currently exists?&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: Ideally, resources, digital accessibility and digital literacy should be available for every pupil on an equal basis. But I think perhaps if we analysed this in" />
    <node id="The creators of digital resources for learning have incorporated insights from higher education (HE) professionals by having some of these individuals directly contribute ideas to the development process. This is done to ensure that support resources align with assessment objectives in many subjects that are shifting towards evaluation and analysis. Moreover, teachers who provide ideas for digital resources are aware of the progression to HE and develop materials emphasizing an analysis-based learning approach, keeping in mind the needs of learners transitioning to higher education. Additionally, HE professionals collaborate to create curriculum-focused resources that encourage students to analyze, synthesize information, and develop discursive argument skills, moving away from textbook-based learning models. The WJEC, a Welsh examination board, plays a significant role in this process by leveraging its expertise in GCSE and A-level materials to contribute to resources for lower levels, ensuring continuity in the learning experience and better preparing students for the transition to tertiary education." />
    <node id="Yes, it is possible to reconcile a national approach and collaboration in developing the Welsh curriculum while maintaining a separation between the textbook and the dominant exam board's approach. This can be achieved by focusing on creating a common core of resources that are available for learners and teachers, including textbooks, which serve as fundamental resources for learners and teachers, particularly during exam periods. The key is to ensure that these textbooks are developed in parallel with the curriculum and are not overly influenced by the specific exam board's approach.&#10;&#10;In this context, the Welsh Government, WJEC, and publishers are currently implementing an experiment to ensure equity in the release of new textbooks in both Welsh and English languages, addressing concerns about different timetables for the availability of learning materials in different languages. The agreement between these parties is a collaboration rather than a mandate, aiming to change the current practice where most publishers and authors work through the medium of English, causing delays in the production of Welsh-medium materials.&#10;&#10;However, there are challenges that need to be considered, such as the complexity of academic journal articles being used at GCSE level due to their inherent complexity, making scholarly websites more accessible for students, and avoiding teaching to the test by creating more sample assessments. Additionally, collaboration is needed to identify high-quality resources worth translating and make them available early on, particularly in Welsh-medium schools where many resources and case studies are available only in English.&#10;&#10;By focusing on these aspects and maintaining open communication between all parties involved, it is possible to create a national approach that benefits both the learners and teachers while preserving the necessary separation between textbooks and the dominant exam board's approach." />
    <node id=" board, and you have a Welsh curriculum that's developed with that board, how do you then have this separation between textbook and exam?&#10;Speaker: Philip Blaker&#10;Content: So, if we look at qualification, a qualification should be based on the curriculum that's being offered, because learning should be based around the curriculum, and the role of the qualification is to measure attainment against knowledge of that curriculum—knowledge, skills and understanding, the dispositions that that curriculum is trying to develop. So, I think there are two very distinct things. Now, of course, what will inevitably happen is once the curriculum is known and developed, there will be a level of detail that comes across from what the qualification is looking for. I think what we're trying to say is, from an educational perspective, what we'd like to see is a broader focus on the curriculum and less of a narrow focus on the qualification and some of the problems that that can drive, so that, if a learner is well-versed in the curriculum and has been taught well and has acquired the knowledge, skills and dispositions that the curriculum is trying to create, they should succeed in the qualification.&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: And you suggested earlier that" />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Government has asked publisher Hodder Education, along with other publishers, to delay the English version of certain textbooks as an experiment to ensure equity in the release of new textbooks in both Welsh and English languages. This decision is in response to concerns about different timetables for the availability of learning materials in different languages.&#10;2. Hodder Education and other publishers have agreed to this request, but it only applies to textbooks currently in development and not those that are already late. The eight-week period for translation and editing is intended for new textbooks moving forward.&#10;3. Hodder Education is open to the idea of producing Welsh-medium textbooks first and then translating them into English, which is a new approach being implemented as an experiment at the request of the Welsh Government. However, they can only work on those books that are in the process of being developed.&#10;4. Hodder Education acknowledges the concern about delaying English versions of textbooks by two months but emphasizes the importance of equitable treatment for both languages. They are open to a chapter-by-chapter approach to mitigate this issue." />
    <node id="1. Impact on teachers' planning: The delayed provision of educational resources such as textbooks, marking criteria, and specimen papers can hinder teachers' ability to prepare adequately for their lessons. This is because they might not have enough time or appropriate materials to create well-structured lesson plans that address the learning objectives effectively.&#10;2. Differential availability and demand: The impact of this delay may vary across subjects, as some subjects might have a higher demand for exemplars or textbooks than others. This inconsistency in resource availability can exacerbate the challenges faced by teachers in planning their lessons, further affecting pupils' achievement.&#10;3. Reduction in attainment: Estyn has reported reduced attainment during periods of change to an exam or qualification due to factors like teachers' unfamiliarity with specifications and requirements, limited access to past assessment resources, and increased concerns about being the first to sit an exam. These challenges are more pronounced when resources are delayed or inadequate.&#10;4. Teaching to the test: An overemphasis on sample assessments can lead to teaching to the test, narrowing the curriculum's scope and limiting opportunities for students to develop a broader range of skills and knowledge.&#10;5. Reduced focus on deeper learning: Overreliance on sample assessments may shift attention away from deeper learning objectives like analysis and evaluation towards test-taking strategies or content mastery, which might not adequately prepare students for real-world situations or higher education.&#10;6. Mitigating issues through future reforms: Adjusting the timeline for producing resources like textbooks and other curriculum materials that support assessment objectives focusing on analysis and evaluation can help mitigate these potential risks. By diversifying available learning materials, educators can create more balanced learning experiences that do not solely focus on test-taking strategies or content.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, the delay in providing textbooks, sample assessments, and exemplars can significantly impact teachers' ability to plan lessons and subsequently affect pupils' achievement. This effect is influenced by the differential availability and demand for resources across various subjects, as well as the potential risks associated with teaching to the test and reduced focus on deeper learning. Addressing these challenges through future reforms and diversifying available learning materials can help mitigate these issues and promote a more balanced approach to education." />
    <node id="1. Emphasize teacher autonomy: Encourage and support teachers in interpreting and providing the curriculum according to their students' needs, contexts, and interests. This can lead to more engaged learners and effective teaching. Teachers should be provided with resources that support their autonomy rather than dictating specific qualification-focused materials.&#10;2. Diversify resource offerings: Encourage a variety of resources from different providers to support the curriculum. This could include textbooks, digital resources, and other educational materials that help teachers tailor their instruction to their students' needs while covering the necessary curriculum objectives.&#10;3. Leverage consortia: Consortia in the United States emphasize teacher autonomy and suggest that there might be less need for national resources or that such resources should support teachers' autonomy. Collaborate with these consortia or create similar structures to develop and provide resources that empower teachers and adapt to local needs.&#10;4. Adjust regulations: Encourage Welsh providers like the WJEC to take on a larger role in addressing the shortage of resource providers in Wales by creating an enabling environment for them to participate in the market. Revise regulations to allow these providers to engage more actively in producing and publishing resources, which can contribute to a more diverse range of offerings for Welsh schools.&#10;5. Shift the timeline for producing curriculum materials: By focusing on curriculum resources rather than qualification resources, the production timeline for some materials can be changed. This approach can help ensure that a broader range of topics and knowledge are covered in classrooms, even if they are no longer part of the specific qualification criteria." />
    <node id=" a curriculum resource, rather than a qualification resource, I think we can change the timeline to which some of those materials are produced. So, going back to when I studied my A-levels in the 1980s, there was this common body of knowledge that was an A-level textbook in biology that wasn't focused around an individual awarding body. When we talked to unions about this on Monday, they said, 'Yes, when we used to teach many years ago, there were curriculum resources like that, and then when a particular topic or a particular area of content dropped out of the qualification, we either did or didn't teach it according to whether it was in the curriculum'. That's a little bit worrying by virtue of the fact there might have been a component of that subject that didn't get taught because it was no longer in the text, despite the fact that it was in the common body of knowledge. But I think if we can shift this paradigm—and I would really like to a shift in the paradigm for resources particularly, away from the focus on the qualification and into more of a focus on the curriculum—then that provides an opportunity for, I would suggest, a much healthier model in the future. There are various ways of doing that. In the United States" />
    <node id="1. To ensure that Welsh-medium textbooks are available simultaneously with their English counterparts, the WJEC and publishers like Hodder and Illuminate have agreed to produce the Welsh versions first and then translate them into English. The translation and editing process will happen concurrently as the textbook is written, with an eight-week period set aside for this purpose. Changes made after approval may cause delays, so chapters will be approved as they are completed to reduce the likelihood of major changes later on.&#10;2. A risk mitigation measure being implemented is the approval of chapters as they are completed, reducing the likelihood of major changes later on that could cause delays. The eight-week period for translation and editing aims to ensure that both versions will be available simultaneously, with draft versions of the English textbook possibly made available earlier. However, final publication of both versions will be held until the Welsh version is complete.&#10;3. This approach only applies to new textbooks currently in development, as the focus is on ensuring equity in the release of new textbooks moving forward. If an English version of a textbook is already late in development, the agreed-upon eight-week period for translation and editing may not apply. Producing Welsh-medium textbooks first and then translating them into English is a new approach being implemented as an experiment at the request of the Welsh Government." />
    <edge source="1. Teachers providing ideas for digital resources are aware of the progression to HE and what their learners want, and they develop support resources that emphasize the importance of an analysis-based learning approach. (Gareth Pierce)&#10;2. Higher education professionals contributing ideas also promote this approach, as it aligns with assessment objectives in many subjects shifting towards evaluation and analysis. (Hefin David AM)&#10;3. However, there is a challenge in using academic journal articles, common in HE-level analysis-based learning, at GCSE level due to the complexity of such materials. (Hefin David AM)&#10;4. Websites pointing to scholarly resources can be useful, but they need to be made accessible and user-friendly for students to engage with and understand the themes. (Gareth Pierce)&#10;5. The WJEC has collaborated with publishers in the past to produce resources for key stage 3 and primary stages, and if it continues to be a player in GCSE and A-level qualifications, it can contribute to key stage 3 and possibly primary stages as well. (Gareth Pierce)&#10;&#10;In summary, teachers and HE professionals providing ideas for digital resources have incorporated curriculum-focused resources and an analysis-based learning approach by being mindful of the learners' needs and the shift in assessment objectives at higher education levels. While there are challenges in implementing this approach at lower levels, efforts are being made to assist students in engaging with scholarly materials and understanding themes, as well as making resources more accessible for teachers and students. The WJEC has also collaborated with publishers to create resources that support the transition from key stage 3 to GCSE level." target=" higher education background, what I've tried to deliver in my courses are textbook-free modules, where you're relying on academic journal articles and you're piecing together the story yourself, based on the curriculum you 