    <edge source=" methods. But in some subjects the demand has been so strong that we have worked with schools in order to ensure that work is produced by pupils before that first examination, is marked by us, and is then made available. So, we can respond to that demand when it arises. I would like to have a conversation with Estyn, indeed, to interpret on a more detailed level some of the things that they refer to.&#10;Speaker: Emyr George&#10;Content: May I offer a comment on that quote from Estyn? They talk about a reduction in attainment and that, to some extent, brings us back to the point in terms of the comparable outcomes method that we're talking about. That method is based on research and evidence that says that in a period of change to an exam or qualification, we know that performance in an exam can fall, and that is due to a number of different factors. Teachers aren't as familiar with the specification and the requirements of the exam. There are fewer past assessment resources available; there aren't any past papers, for example. Certainly, knowing that you're the first to sit that exam perhaps raises your concerns about that examination, and examinations are a matter of concern already. It's very difficult, if not impossible," target="1. Estyn has reported delays in the production and distribution of educational resources such as textbooks, marking criteria, and specimen papers.&#10;2. These delays have impeded teachers' ability to plan adequately, which is likely to have had an impact on pupils' achievement.&#10;3. Estyn links three different issues: textbooks, sample assessments with approved marking schemes, and exemplars of student work.&#10;4. While sample assessments are statutorily available within the regulatory time frame, exemplars can only be made available digitally or through various other methods after students have taken their exams for the first time.&#10;5. Estyn has noted a reduction in attainment due to various factors during periods of change to an exam or qualification, including teachers' unfamiliarity with specifications and requirements, fewer past assessment resources, and increased concerns about being the first to sit an exam.&#10;6. WJEC agrees that ideally, the whole package of resources should be available before teaching starts, but acknowledges that performance can fall during periods of change due to multiple factors.&#10;7. Estyn has had recent meetings with WJEC to discuss these concerns, and will continue to do so.">
