    <edge source=" wave. Well, what about the tsunami of curriculum reform that we're currently facing? That is, how confident can we be that the situation won't deteriorate as the new curriculum is introduced—rather than improve?&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: That is a very key question, isn't it? We have started to discuss this, specifically in particular in a forum that includes publishers in Wales, with the Welsh Government around the table and Qualifications Wales around the table. I think one of the very interesting questions and important questions is: what will the nature of the information available in April 2019 be in terms of the new curriculum? At what level of detail will it be? To what extent will it be adapted again after April 2019? Is it detailed enough, really, for teachers to start discussing their programmes of teaching, and that we then still have a role with publishers, even though this is for this curriculum and not for qualifications? WJEC has a tradition of publishing resources over the key stages and other key stages as well. I think there is a need to discuss the implications of the timetable as it starts to appear, because there is a need to start teaching the new curriculum in September 2022. If we're talking about a year of preparation," target="1. The WJEC is a Welsh examination board that has historically collaborated with publishers to produce resources for key stage 3 and primary stages. It also aspires to continue being a significant player in the creation of GCSE and A-level qualifications.&#10;2. Given its experience and expertise in creating resources for GCSE and A-levels, which are closely linked to key stage 3, the WJEC is well positioned to contribute to resources for lower levels. This is particularly true if they continue to invest in editing, translating, and utilizing technology for educational materials.&#10;3. By working with academic institutions and HE professionals, the WJEC can ensure that resources for GCSE and A-levels align with assessment objectives that emphasize evaluation and analysis. This approach can then be adapted for key stage 3 and primary stages, making resources more accessible and engaging for students at these levels.&#10;4. Although there might be challenges in implementing analysis-based learning at lower levels due to the complexity of materials, websites and other platforms can help by pointing students towards scholarly resources while maintaining user-friendliness and accessibility. This would enable students to better understand themes and engage with more advanced concepts.">
