    <edge source="1. Complexity of academic journal articles: There is a challenge in using academic journal articles, which are common in HE-level analysis-based learning, at GCSE level due to the complexity of such materials (Hefin David AM).&#10;2. Making scholarly websites accessible: Websites pointing to scholarly resources can be useful, but they need to be made accessible and user-friendly for students to engage with and understand the themes (Gareth Pierce).&#10;3. Teaching to the test: Creating more sample assessments could increase the risk of teaching to the test, further complicating the situation (Gareth Pierce).&#10;4. Independent study skills: The Welsh baccalaureate and skills challenge certificate are designed to help students develop independent study skills relevant for higher education (Philip Blaker).&#10;5. Relevance in a global context: Many resources and case studies are available only in English, which may not be ideal for Welsh-medium schools. Collaboration is needed to identify high-quality resources worth translating and make them available early on (Mark Reckless AM).&#10;6. Vision for teaching in Welsh-medium classes: There should be a vision for enriching teaching in Welsh-medium A-level classes, taking advantage of both the Welsh language and English resources (Mark Reckless AM)." target="1. Collaboration and Identification of High-Quality Resources: To utilize both English and Welsh resources effectively in Welsh-medium schools, there should be collaboration between schools and stakeholders to identify high-quality resources worth translating. This can help prevent duplication of efforts and optimize teachers' time.&#10;&#10;2. National Approach for Resource Creation: The Welsh Government, WJEC, and publishers are working together to create a national approach for resource creation, focusing on developing a common core of resources available for learners and teachers in both languages. This includes an experiment to ensure equity in the release of new textbooks in both Welsh and English.&#10;&#10;3. Awareness of Digitally Available Resources: Gareth Pierce mentioned that there are many resources available digitally in both languages at the same time. Teachers should be made aware of these resources to reduce the need for independent translations and duplication of efforts.&#10;&#10;4. Balancing Act between Languages: The vision for teaching in Welsh-medium classes should aim to enrich the learning experience by taking advantage of both the Welsh language and English resources. This can help create a more comprehensive and balanced educational environment.&#10;&#10;5. Addressing the Root Cause of Translation Needs: It is essential to understand what causes the need for translations in order to address the issue effectively. By identifying the source of the problem, stakeholders can work together to find solutions that benefit both learners and teachers.">
