    <edge source=" we will have an opportunity to explore their comments here I'm sure.&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: Looking at the structure and the relationship between Qualifications Wales and the WJEC—. I understand in the model in England—you've got Ofqual, the regulator, and you have various competing exam boards, some I think with for-profit motivation. We don't have that in Wales; there is a sole regulator and a single, dominant examination board. Does that mean that there's significant overlap and potentially cost duplication between the work of the two bodies, particularly given WJEC is a charity and seems to have many of the same objectives as you in Qualifications Wales have?&#10;Speaker: Philip Blaker&#10;Content: The roles are very distinct, so I'd tell you there's no overlap. What we try and do is try and make sure that there's a good connection between the work that we do. WJEC has very clear responsibilities around the delivery of qualifications. We have a role in monitoring to ensure that those qualifications are delivered securely and fairly. I would say a strength of the Welsh model is that there is an independent regulator and a single awarding body largely," target="1. Investing in digital resources is a priority for the WJEC, as they have already allocated significant funds from their budget towards developing digital materials. These investments are based on conversations with teachers to identify needs and set priorities.&#10;2. The WJEC sees value in continuing these conversations with teachers, as they provide valuable insights into areas that require attention and help inform decision-making regarding resource allocation.&#10;3. There is room for further integration of digital resources, and additional resources might be necessary to achieve this. However, the specific requirements and potential costs have not been discussed in detail during the transcripts provided.&#10;4. The WJEC has a history of collaborating with publishers to produce resources for key stage 3 and primary stages, leveraging their expertise in creating GCSE and A-level materials. This experience positions them well to contribute to lower-level resources by adapting analysis-based learning approaches and utilizing technology.&#10;5. To address concerns about curriculum reform and the introduction of new curriculum, the WJEC is engaging in discussions with relevant stakeholders, including publishers and the Welsh Government, to ensure a smooth transition and maintain resource quality.">
