    <edge source=", over recent years, to ensure that that delay between having an English version and a Welsh version is reduced. We are highly aware of the fact that the best-case scenario is that the Welsh and the English are available simultaneously. In those terms, we've taken huge steps forward with the publishers that we've named this morning, so that we have discussed translation as the textbook is being produced. There is a risk there, of course. The nature of books is that the author may change his or her mind, or edit as he or she is writing. Well, with that model, we would have to ensure that we approved as we moved forward, chapter by chapter perhaps, so that there would be no changes to be made from then on. At the end of the process, then, the publishers in England have agreed to hold the English version back for a period of time until the Welsh version is available, and then to publish both simultaneously. Unless that timetable is followed throughout the process, there are inherent risks in that process, of course, as I've mentioned in terms of translation as we author materials, and in ensuring that that timetable is stuck to.&#10;Speaker: Gareth Pierce&#10;Content: And perhaps there is a need to emphasise that the process is translation" target="1. For new textbooks being developed, the Welsh-medium version will be completed and published simultaneously with the English version. The Welsh version will be translated from the English original, with editing and translation happening concurrently as the textbook is written. An eight-week period has been agreed upon for this process, to ensure that both versions are available at the same time. Draft versions of the English textbook may be made available earlier, but final publication will be held until the Welsh version is complete.&#10;2. However, if an English version of a textbook is already late in development, the agreed-upon eight-week period for translation and editing may not apply. This is because the focus is on ensuring equity in the release of new textbooks moving forward, rather than delaying texts that have already been delayed.&#10;3. It's important to note that producing Welsh-medium textbooks first and then translating them into English is an approach that publishers like Hodder and Illuminate are open to, but it has not been the standard practice in the past. This new approach is being implemented as an experiment at the request of the Welsh Government.">
