    <edge source="Yes, it is accepted that some students have been negatively affected by the lack of suitable support materials for general qualifications. There is evidence of their concern, even though it may be challenging to establish a direct cause-and-effect relationship between anxiety from resource limitations and lower attainment due to the presence of multiple factors and resources that could impact student performance." target="The creators of digital resources for learning have incorporated insights from higher education (HE) professionals by having some of these individuals directly contribute ideas to the development process. This is done to ensure that support resources align with assessment objectives in many subjects that are shifting towards evaluation and analysis. Moreover, teachers who provide ideas for digital resources are aware of the progression to HE and develop materials emphasizing an analysis-based learning approach, keeping in mind the needs of learners transitioning to higher education. Additionally, HE professionals collaborate to create curriculum-focused resources that encourage students to analyze, synthesize information, and develop discursive argument skills, moving away from textbook-based learning models. The WJEC, a Welsh examination board, plays a significant role in this process by leveraging its expertise in GCSE and A-level materials to contribute to resources for lower levels, ensuring continuity in the learning experience and better preparing students for the transition to tertiary education.">
